org.eclipse.ecf.remoteservice.rest
Interface IRestCall

All Known Implementing Classes:
DeleteRestCall, GetRestCall, PostRestCall, PutRestCall, RestCall
public interface IRestCall

This class acts as a container for a specific REST service call. It can be implemented from scratch or created via RestCallFactory.

Method Detail

getEstimatedResourceIdentifier

java.lang.String getEstimatedResourceIdentifier()
Every rest web service returns a resource representation. I.e a representation as a xml file from a xml resource.

Returns:
the identifier for a estimated resource, i.e. ecf.rest.resource.xml. Will not be null.

getURI

java.net.URI getURI()
Defines the URI for the rest service. This should be a unique URI which belongs to a rest service i.e on the web.

Returns:
the URI of a rest service. Will not be null.

getMethod

java.lang.String getMethod()
Defines the HTTP method for this type of rest call. For example a GET or POST method.

Returns:
the HTTP Method as one of the IRestCall HTTP_* constants. Will not be null.

getRequestHeaders

java.util.Map getRequestHeaders()
Defines the call specific request headers.

Returns:
a Map object which contains the header parameters. May be null.

getParameters

java.lang.Object[] getParameters()
Defines the key-value pairs parameter for this call. A Rest Call may either have parameters or a RequestEntity (mutual exclusive).

Returns:
an array containing key-value pairs in the format: key=value. May be null.
See Also:
getRequestEntity()

getTimeout

long getTimeout()
Get timeout (in ms) for the rest call.

Returns:
long timeout in ms

getRequestEntity

org.apache.commons.httpclient.methods.RequestEntity getRequestEntity()
Gets the request entity. The RequestEntity is typically used to transmit data by HTTP_POST and HTTP_PUT calls. HTTP_GET calls may not use a request entity A. Rest Call may either have parameters or a RequestEntity (mutual exclusive)

Returns:
the request entity
